article.headline: Colorado 74, California 63
article.story:
BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- With Colorado's lead whittled to five
points, the Buffaloes put the ball in the hands of their clutch
players.

Tera Bjorklund and Kate Fagan hit back-to-back baskets in the
final two minutes, and No. 20 Colorado defeated California 74-63
Saturday night in the championship game of the Coors Classic.

Idaho State beat Lehigh 95-52 in the consolation game.

Bjorklund finished with 21 points and nine rebounds and was
named the tournament MVP.

The Buffs (5-1) also got 14 points from freshman Emily Waner and
13 apiece from Randie Wirt and Kate Fagan. Wirt added 10 rebounds.

Nihan Anaz scored 17 points to lead California (3-1), which
committed 30 turnovers. LaTasha O'Keith had 15 points and Leigh
Gregory added 14 points and eight rebounds.

The Buffaloes held a double-digit lead for much of the second
half, but twice Cal cut the deficit to five points.

Eight straight points by California, including six by Anaz,
trimmed the lead to 40-35 early in the second half, but Colorado
built the lead back to 14.

The Bears' 12-3 run, which included five points each by Anaz and
Gregory, made it 63-58 with 2:36 remaining. But Bjorklund promptly
hit a layup on a feed from Veronica Johns-Richardson, Fagan made a
long 3-pointer and Johns-Richardson made two free throws for a
70-58 edge with 46 seconds left.

Fagan's 3-pointer, from about 25 feet, just beat the shot clock.

"We worked the ball around and couldn't get it into Tera, so we
had to make something else happen," Fagan said. "I looked up and
saw the clock, so I just threw the ball up there. Those things are
not really skill. It's more luck than anything."

Colorado had 19 steals, which coach Ceal Barry attributed to the
fact that Cal runs the same offense as Colorado.

"Our players might have jumped in on a couple of passes because
they have the same offense," Barry said. "We knew most of the
things they were going to throw at us.

"Our real problem was missing a bunch of layups. That really
hurt. We were never able to run away with the game, so you have to
give credit to Cal. They played us tough."

Barry used only a seven-play rotation because of injuries.

"Having Anna (Nedovic) and Whitney (Law) out really hurts our
depth," she said. "They were our eighth and ninth players."

California coach Caren Horstmeyer said turnovers made the
difference.

"The goal is to force the other team to turn the ball over, and
we were the ones turning it over," she said. "We had 30 turnovers
and they had 18, and Colorado's defense was forcing them. They did
a great job defensively."

Bjorklund had 11 points in the first half as Colorado, using a
15-0 run, took a 36-25 halftime lead.

Fagan and Amber Metoyer each hit 3-pointers during that flurry.
After California cut the deficit to seven, Bjorklund scored five
straight Colorado points to help push the lead back to 11.
